{"add":{"doc":{"id":"6d9d551089d6f87cb2d03ea93a28271ace7cc937e8dbe079277ce25d583a58b3","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/df/British_Expeditionary_Force_in_Freetown%2C_1919.jpg/250px-British_Expeditionary_Force_in_Freetown%2C_1919.jpg","previous":["For several months, Bureh's fighters had the advantage over the vastly more powerful British forces. Both the British troops and Bureh's warriors suffered hundreds of fatalities each.[29] Bai Bureh finally surrendered on 11 November 1898 to end the destruction of his people's territory and dwellings. Although the British government recommended leniency, Cardew insisted on sending the chief and two allies into exile in the Gold Coast;[28] his government hanged 96 of the chief's warriors. Bai Bureh was allowed to return in 1905, when he resumed his chieftaincy of Kasseh.[28]"],"after":["The defeat of the Temne and Mende in the Hut Tax war ended large-scale organized resistance to the Protectorate and colonial government. But, resistance continued throughout the colonial period in the form of intermittent, wide-scale rioting and chaotic labour disturbances. For instance, riots in 1955 and 1956 involved \"many tens of thousands\" of natives in the protectorate.[30]"]}}}